factor (N)  is not sufficient to do this.For this reason less then 20 % pure material can not be used in A- bombs. It can only be used in power reactors as fuel.<br>
Tim <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=yales>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 1149<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(5/3/03 10:57 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=148.topic&index=26>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Plutonium Blast At Wall Street Journal</span><hr size=1> First of all, U233 can go as low as 12% or so, but that is not what the issue is really about.<br>
<br>
<br>
What you are confused about is is the percentage of an plutonium in a mixed element fuel rod (which may be a small amount of Pu and a bunch of uranium) and the isotopic blend of the plutonium itself.<br>
<br>
Yes, the amount of Pu239 in a MOX rod may be only 5 percent (and thus non-explosive), However, the weapon-builder dissolves or melts the fuel rod, adds a chemical which reacts with plutonium and not uranium, and thus separates the plutonium from the uranium. Now you have essentially pure bomb grade Pu239.<br>
<br>
yale<br>
